bruary 2012).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Duncan|1917}}|reference=Duncan, William Edmondstoune. 1917. ''Ultra-Modernism in Music: A Treatise on the Latter-day Revolution in Musical Art''. Schirmer's Red Series of Music Text Books. London: Winthrop Rogers.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Earle|2011}}|reference=Earle, Benjamin. 2011. ''Luigi Dallapiccola and Musical Modernism in Fascist Italy''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-84403-1}} (cloth); e-book reprint 2013, {{ISBN|978-1-107-41638-3}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Everdell|1997}}|reference=[[William Everdell|Everdell, William]]. 1997. \"Arnold Schoenberg: Music in No Key\". In [[The First Moderns|''The First Moderns: Profiles in the Origins of Twentieth-Century Thought'',]] {{Page needed|date=February 2017}}<!--Inclusive page numbers of the chapter are needed.--> Chicago: University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0-226-22480-5}} (cloth); {{ISBN|0-226-22481-3}} (paperback).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Ferneyhough|1995}}|reference=Ferneyhough, Brian. 1995. ''Collected Writings'', edited by James Boros and Richard Toop. New York: Routledge. {{ISBN|3-7186-5577-2}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Frisch|2005}}|reference=Frisch, Walter. 2005. ''German Modernism: Music and the Arts''. California Studies in 20th-century Music. Berkeley, Los Angeles, and London: University of California Press. {{ISBN|0-520-24301-3}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Griffiths|1981}}|reference=[[Paul Griffiths (writer)|Griffiths, Paul]]. 1981. ''Modern Music: The Avant Garde since 1945''. New York: George Braziller. {{ISBN|0-8076-1018-6}} (pbk).}}\n*Guldbrandsen, Erling E., and Julian Johnson (eds.) 2015. ''Transformations of Musical Modernism''. Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press.  {{ISBN|978-1-107-12721-0}}. \n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Harper-Scott|2012}}|reference=Harper-Scott, J. P. E. 2012. ''The Quilting Points of Musical Modernism: Revolution, Reaction, and William Walton''. Music in Context. Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-76521-3}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Hess|2001}}|reference=Hess, Carol A. 2001. ''Manuel de Falla and Modernism in Spain, 1898-1936''. Chicago Studies in the History of Judaism. Chicago: University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|978-0-226-33038-9}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Hisama|2006}}|reference=Hisama, Ellie M. 2006. ''Gendering Musical Modernism: The Music of Ruth Crawford, Marion Bauer, and Miriam Gideon''. Cambridge Studies in Music Theory and Analysis 15. Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-521-02843-1}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Loya|2011}}|reference=Loya, Shay. 2011. ''Liszt's Transcultural Modernism and the Hungarian-Gypsy Tradition''. Eastman Studies in Music. Rochester, NY: University of Rochester Press. {{ISBN|9781580463232}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Riley|2010}}|reference=Riley, Matthew (ed.). 2010. ''British Music and Modernism, 1895\u20131960''. Aldershot: Ashgate. {{ISBN|978-0-7546-6585-4}}.}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Schleifer|first1=Ronald|title=Modernism and Popular Music|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-65530-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Sitsky|2002}}|reference=Sitsky, Larry. 2002. ''Music of the Twentieth-Century Avant-garde: A Biocritical Sourcebook''. Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press. {{ISBN|0-313-29689-8}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Smith Brindle|1987}}|reference=[[Reginald Smith Brindle|Smith Brindle, Reginald]]. 1987. ''The New Music: The Avant-garde Since 1945'', second edition. Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-315471-4}} (cloth) {{ISBN|0-19-315468-4}} (pbk).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Straus|1990}}|reference=Straus, Joseph Nathan. 1990. ''Remaking the Past: Musical Modernism and the Influence of the Tonal Tradition''. Cambridge, Massachusetts.: Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|0-674-75990-7}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Russolo|1913}}|reference=Russolo, Luigi. 1913.'' L'arte dei rumori: manifesto futurista''. Milan: Direzione del Movimento Futurista.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Taruskin|1987}}|reference=Taruskin, Richard. 1987. \"The First Modernist\". ''The New Republic'' 197, no. 26 (28 December): 36\u201340. Reprinted in: Richard Taruskin, ''The Danger of Music and other Anti-Utopian Essays'', 195\u2013201. Berkeley and Los Angeles: University of California Press, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-520-24977-6}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Watkins|1994}}|reference=[[Glenn Watkins|Watkins, Glenn]]. 1994. ''Pyramids at the Louvre: Music, Culture, and Collage from Stravinsky to the Postmodernists''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Belknap Press of Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|0-674-74083-1}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Williams|1999}}|reference=Williams, Alastair. 1999. \"Adorno and the Semantics of Modernism\". ''Perspectives of New Music'' 37, no. 2 (Summer): 29\u201350.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Youmans|2005}}|reference=Youmans,  Charles Dowell. 2005. ''Richard Strauss's Orchestral Music and the German Intellectual Tradition: The Philosophical Roots of Musical Modernism''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press. {{ISBN|0-253-34573-1}}.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ronsheim.org Audio lectures on the history of the Modern musical era by Prof. John Ronsheim]\n\n{{Modernism}}\n{{Modernism (music)}}\n\n[[Category:Modernism (music)| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jerome Kohl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modernism_(music)"}
{"title_page": "John Cullen Nugent", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian artist}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n|honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=CAN|size=100%|RCA}}\n|birth_place = [[Montreal]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1921|01|05}}\n|death_place = [[Lumsden, Saskatchewan]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|df=y|2014|03|12|1921|01|05}}\n|known_for   = [[liturgical]] and [[public sculpture]], [[photography]]\n|training    = [[College of Saint Benedict and Saint John's University|Saint John's University]]\n|works = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Louis Riel Memorial (Nugent)|Louis Riel Memorial]]\n*''[[No. 1 Northern]]''\n}}\n|nationality = Canadian\n|spouse      = Florence Keller\n}}\n'''John Cullen Nugent''' was a Canadian artist and educator known primarily for his [[public art]] works, often in the form of [[abstract sculpture]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Montreal]] on 5 January 1921,<ref name=\"Seitz\">{{cite book |last1=Seitz |first1=Elizabeth |title=UNIVERSITY OF REGINA ARCHIVES AND SPECIAL COLLECTIONSTHE DR JOHN ARCHER LIBRARY: 97-43 JOHN NUGENT |date=2009 |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |page=2 |url=https://www.uregina.ca/library/assets/docs/pdf/finding_aids/97_43.pdf |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> the young Nugent attended high school in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] before returning to Canada prior to the [[Second World War]] and joining the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], training at [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] and [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"Longman\">{{cite news |last1=Longman |first1=Harold |title=Ancient art practiced at Lumsden by west's only candlestick maker |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/494968855/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |date=March 9, 1957 |page=2}}</ref> Three years later, Nugent joined the [[Canadian Army]], serving in the [[Provost (military police)|provost corps]] in the 1940s.<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news |title=Influential Sask. artist, John Nugent, dies at 93 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/influential-sask-artist-john-nugent-dies-at-93-1.2578796 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |work=CBC News |agency=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=March 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war, Nugent was discharged and studied art at [[College of Saint Benedict and Saint John's University|St John's University]] ([[Collegeville, Minnesota]]),<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> where he was exposed to liberal ideals and the postwar Catholic renewal in the arts.<ref name=\"Long\">{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Timothy |title=John Cullen Nugent |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/john-cullen-nugent |website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> There, he was apprenticed in sculpture and silversmith work with Donald Humphrey, and later obtained additional training after moving to [[Lumsden, Saskatchewan]] in 1947.<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"SKNAC\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent |url=http://www.sknac.ca/index.php?page=ArtistDetail&id=21 |website=sknac.ca |publisher=Saskatchewan Network for Art Collecting |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nNugent attended the [[Emma Lake, Saskatchewan|Emma Lake]] Artists' Workshops in the 1950s and 1960s, studying with [[Jack Shadbolt]], [[Joseph Plaskett]], [[Will Barnet]], and [[Clement Greenberg]].<ref name=\"SKNAC\" />\n\n==Career in the arts==\n===Religious works and candle making===\nIn Lumsden, Nugent established his first studio (formerly a [[barn]]) and [[bronze casting]] foundry on a 2.7-hectare parcel of land that forms the north slope of the [[Qu\u2019Appelle Valley]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"SKNAC\" /><ref name=\"Studio\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent Studio |url=https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=5859 |website=Canada's Historic Places |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> He received numerous commissions in the decades following,<ref name=\"SKNAC\" /> initially producing religious sculptures in silver and bronze ([[liturgical]] commissions, including chalices and candleholders) while supporting his family as a [[candle|chandler]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"Long2\">{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Timothy |title=Nugent, John Cullen (1921-) |url=https://esask.uregina.ca/entry/nugent_john_cullen_1921-.jsp |website=The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> According to Timothy Long, these works were \"simplified, yet expressive\": chalices and crucifixes which demonstrated Nugent's interest in modern interpretations of early Christian and [[Romanesque sculpture|Romanesque]] models.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> Candle making was a lucrative sideline, Nugent being the only maker west of [[Windsor, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /> The Shop's wick material was specially woven from [[beeswax]] bought from the beekeepers co-operative processing plant at [[Tisdale, Saskatchewan|Tisdale]] and treated with a solution, the ingredients of which were a [[trade secret]] taught to him by L. H. Shirley, a [[Roman Catholic priest]] in [[Young, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"Longman\" />\n\n===New studio===\n{{Main|John Nugent Studio}}\nIn 1960, Nugent's candle works in Lumsden burned down. Nugent commissioned [[Clifford Wiens]] to design a new studio with a novel curved, conical design that earned the architect a Massey silver medal.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> The studio was constructed over successive weekends by Nugent and Wiens, with help from fellow artists [[Kenneth Lochhead]] and [[Roy Kiyooka]].<ref name=\"Studio\" /> The studio has been a Provincial Heritage Property since 26 May 2005, the 42nd site so designated, and listed at the online [[Canadian Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"GOS\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent Studio Designated a Provincial Heritage Property |url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2005/november/25/john-nugent-studio-designated-a-provincial-heritage-property |website=Saskatchewan.ca |publisher=[[Government of Saskatchewan]] |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Turn to abstract sculpture===\nResistance from the Church hierarchy and from parishioners led to Nugent abandoning his liturgical work in the 1960s.<ref name=\"Long\" /><ref name=\"Long2\" /> After meeting American sculptor [[David Smith (sculptor)|David Smith]] in New York in 1961, Nugent was in any case gradually shifting to welded steel abstracts, for which he is now best known, and which exhibit what Long calls \"an awkward grace\" in its [[constructivism (art)|constructivist]] [[collage]] of prefabricated steel elements.<ref name=\"Long\"/> He acquired some of the raw materials from the [[SSAB#North American operations|IPSCO Steel]] steel company in Regina, and often gave the pieces names \"to eliminate distraction from the form itself\".<ref name=\"Campus\">{{cite web |title=John Cullen Nugent |url=http://www2.uregina.ca/president/art/outdoor/john-cullen-nugent/ |website=Campus Art Guide |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Long describes how Nugent's work differentiates itself from that of others:<blockquote>While often incorporating identifiable parts, such as wheels, his sculpture eludes easy metaphorical readings, instead creating meaning through unexpected combinations of forms and materials. Nugent's work represents an independent strain within Canadian abstract steel sculpture without direct ties to the Emma Lake Artists' Workshops or other western Canadian sculptors.<ref name=\"Long2\" /></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Macdonaldstat.jpg|thumb|John A. Macdonald Memorial in [[Victoria Park, Regina]]]]\n\n===Public sculptural works===\nNugent's best known public sculptures are found in the three [[Prairie Provinces]] of Canada, including commissions for places such as the [[Banff Centre]] in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] and the [[Canadian Grain Commission]] building in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"Long\"/> There is a piece in the galleria of the CBC Saskatchewan building in Regina.<ref name=\"Strombo\">{{cite news |title=\"He Taught Us To Consider The Beauty Around Us:\" Remembering Saskatchewan Sculptor John Nugent |url=https://www.cbc.ca/strombo/news/john-nugent-1921-2014 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=George Stromboulopoulos Tonight |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Another public commission is at the [[National Capital Commission]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"Long2\" /> More of his work can be found in the collections of the MacKenzie Art Gallery, the [[Robert McLaughlin Gallery]] ([[Oshawa]]), the [[Saskatchewan Arts Board]], the [[University of Regina]], and the [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]].<ref name=\"Long2\" />\n\nOn occasion, controversy was induced by Nugent's work, including commissions by Saskatchewan Premier [[Ross Thatcher]] and the [[Canadian Grain Commission]].<ref name=\"URL\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent |url=https://www.uregina.ca/library/services/archives/collections/art-architecture/nugent.html |website=University of Regina Library |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====John A. Macdonald Memorial (1967)====\n{{Main|John A. Macdonald Memorial (Grandmaison)}}\nLocal fundraising for a statue in Regina to commemorate the first [[Prime Minister of Canada]] began in 1891, though the work did not begin until 1966 after Sonia de Grandmaison was commissioned to do the work. Her statue of [[Sir John A. Macdonald]] was cast by Nugent using the \"lost wax technique\" he learned along with candlemaking, in five pieces, which were then [[soldering|soldered]] together.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sonia de Grandmaison: Downtown Regina Public Art Guide |date=2014 |publisher=Regina Downtown Business Improvement District |location=Regina |page=14 |url=https://reginadowntown.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/PublicArtGuide2014-101514web.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |chapter=Sir John A. MacDonald (1966-67)}}</ref>\n\n====Louis Riel Memorial (1968)====\n{{Main|Louis Riel Memorial (Nugent)}}\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Riel has significance for people now, and I felt he had to be expressed in contemporary terms.\n| source = John Nugent<ref name=\"MitchellL\">{{cite journal |last1=Mitchell |first1=Linda |title=One sculptor\u2019s racy revenge with an embarrassingly real Riel |journal=Maclean's |date=May 1, 1969 |page=2 |url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1969/5/1/one-sculptors-racy-revenge-with-an-embarrassingly-real-riel |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}} \nIn the lead-up to the [[Canadian Centennial]] in 1967, the Saskatchewan Arts Board recommended that the province should have a new public sculpture.<ref name=\"Chabun0\">{{cite news |last1=Chabun |first1=Will |title=Icons in exile: How Regina's Riel statue and other monuments disappeared from view |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/icons-in-exile-how-reginas-riel-statue-and-other-monuments-disappeared-from-view |accessdate=20 December 2019 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=September 10, 2016}}</ref> To this end, a competition was announced.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent proposed an abstract monument of [[M\u00e9tis]] leader [[Louis Riel]]<ref name=\"URL\" /> in the form of an abstract design in three parts: \"two large plates of steel and a single spike between them\", which Will Chabun suggested could be easily understood as \"two hands reaching out and one other element reaching out to the sky.\"<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> According to Timothy Long, head curator of the [[MacKenzie Art Gallery]], Nugent's idea was to represent an as yet unrealized inspiration.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent's proposal won the competition, but Premier [[Ross Thatcher]] stepped in and made clear his preference for a [[realism (arts)|realistic]] depiction.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> A provincial cabinet meeting followed which included Nugent, representatives from the Board and the [[University of Saskatchewan]], and [[Art McKay]]. All were convinced of the proposal's merit but Premier Thatcher, and he was the only one whose opinion counted.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" />\n\nNugent later said he wanted to refuse but he needed the money. He agreed to design a  sculpture of Riel \"striding forward\", arm raised and pointing upward, maintaining in some way the essence of the original idea.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent's final submission was of this \"heroic\" figure of Riel, which the artist sculpted as a [[nude]].<ref name=\"URL\" /> Objections were again raised,<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> and Nugent was made to add some form of clothing.<ref name=\"URL\" /> He created a \"cape or vest\" made from wax-coated [[burlap]] and wrapped it around the statue's body, covering the [[genitalia]], though not entirely.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> The statue was unveiled in 1968,<ref name=\"URL\" /> near the legislative building.\n\nAs for those whom Riel originally represented, the M\u00e9tis community, no one was ever consulted by anyone involved in the project at any stage,<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> and as time passed mounting pressure came from the M\u00e9tis who requested the work be removed from the legislative grounds.<ref name=\"Chabun1\" /> The defunct ArtsSask.ca website noted their criticisms:<blockquote>John Nugent was not of Metis descent and many people in the Metis community were upset because they had no input in the design. Many also found the sculpture of Riel offensive and were glad to see the memorial removed after it had stood in Wascana Park in Regina for 23 years.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn 1991, the sculpture was removed<ref name=\"URL\" /> and relocated to the MacKenzie Art Gallery vault,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mattes |first1=Catherine L. |title=Whose Hero? Images of Louis Riel in Contemporary Art and M\u00e9tis Nationhood |date=1998 |publisher=[[Concordia University]] |location=Montreal, Quebec |page=15 |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk3/ftp04/mq43534.pdf |accessdate=8 January 2020 |format=M.A. thesis}}</ref> along with Nugent's original abstract maquette, where it remains.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamon |first1=Max |title=[Book review] #226 Rescuing Riel, revising history |website=BC book look |date=December 20, 2017 |url=https://bcbooklook.com/2017/12/20/rescuing-riel-revising-history/ |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''No. 1 Northern'' (1976)====\n{{Main|No. 1 Northern}}\nThis large steel [[abstract sculpture]] is intended as a [[metaphor]] for fields of wheat, represented in multi-layer rectangular shapes and painted the \"brilliant\" yellow of harvest wheat,<ref name=\"White\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Ed |title=Homage to wheat dragged out, dusted off, pieced together |url=https://www.producer.com/1997/05/homage-to-wheat-dragged-out-dusted-off-pieced-together/ |accessdate=18 December 2019 |work=[[The Western Producer]] |date=May 15, 1997}}</ref> designed to represent Canada's hardy top grade, red [[spring wheat]] hybrid of the same name<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\">{{cite book |last1=Anderson-Dolcini |first1=Catherine |title=One-percent for Whom? Canada's Public Works Fine Art Programme, 1964-1978: Its Rise and Demise |date=November 29, 2000 |publisher=[[Carleton University]] |location=Ottawa |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk3/ftp04/MQ57697.pdf |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> that dominate the Prairies in the fall.<ref name=\"White\" /> The work was commissioned following a process begun as a recommendation by the architectural firm [[Smith Carter]] that the recently built [[Canadian Grain Commission]] building should be bestowed with a large scale exterior sculpture.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> Against the objections of Earl Baxter, chairman of the Board of Grain Commissioners, the work was installed in late 1975.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> Baxter canvassed employees, obtaining 300 signatures in protest shortly after the work's 1976 unveiling.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> The federal government's ''Cultural Property Inventory'' cites complaints from employees and the general public that the work was \"ugly and meaningless\", and \"charges that the piece was dangerous in the winter because someone might walk into it and injure themselves.\"<ref name=\"Alfody\">{{cite book |last1=Alfoldy |first1=Sandra |title=The Allied Arts: Architecture and Craft in Postwar Canada |date=2012 |publisher=[[McGill University|McGill]]-[[Queen's University Press]] |location=[Montreal; Kingston, On.] |isbn=9780773539600 |page=147 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VjYH3-zeFeQC&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=no.+1+northern+nugent&source=bl&ots=hxMuRyCYdY&sig=ACfU3U05oYRTGMF6MKDeN1OD-gbL1C1EeA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoi4KNg8HmAhWVKn0KHbWQDdwQ6AEwBXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=no.%201%20northern%20nugent&f=false |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The Agriculture Minister [[Eugene Whelan]] called the work \"a waste of taxpayers' moneys.\"<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> \n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Whelan panned me, the press panned me, people in the building panned me... I was lucky to get out of Winnipeg alive.\n| source = John Nugent<ref name=\"Chabun1\"/>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}  \nBy July 1978, Baxter had prevailed. It was reinstalled two years later in front of a [[Revenue Canada]] building, the Winnipeg Taxation Centre on Stapon Road.<ref name=\"WDP\" /><ref name=\"White\" /> At the time, Nugent said he was not interested in the re-installation, upset that his work had not been supported the first time around and since the sculpture was cut into three \"it wasn't his original work anymore.\"<ref name=\"WDP\">{{cite web |title=No. 1 Northern |url=http://winnipegdowntownplaces.blogspot.com/2009/09/no-1-northern.html |website=Winnipeg Downtown Places |accessdate=19 December 2019 |date=September 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the work was quietly moved a second time,<ref name=\"White\" /> this time to a Winnipeg scrapyard in the salvage area, \"in pieces\", unbeknownst to Nugent, who asked for the public's help in finding the piece.<ref name=\"Alfody\" /> A Public Works spokesperson later said it was because new pathways into the building passed too near the sculpture and the department was concerned \"children might climb on it\".<ref name=\"White\" /> In Spring 1997, Nugent discovered what had become of his work had and complained, with many other artists, about the way Public Works stored pieces of art it owned. The department made a commitment to restoring the sculpture and finding a prominent, public setting for it following public reaction to news of its deterioration.<ref name=\"White\" /> Later the same year, almost twenty years after it was removed, ''No. 1 Northern'' was reinstalled in front of the Grain Commission building.<ref name=\"Grain\">{{cite web |title=[303 Main Street] |url=https://www.winnipegarchitecture.ca/303-main-street/ |website=Winnipeg Architecture Foundation |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====''Tolsop'' (1977)====\nInterested in the three-dimensional forms possible by arranging pieces of [[excess supply|surplus]] steel found at the IPSCO site, Nugent welded a piece that has a very different character when viewed from different angles: while a large convex disc dominates all views, its positioning at 45 degrees \"invites the viewer to consider it from other vantage points,\" so that what initially appears to be a large solid, \"flattish\" and angled piece \"morphs into an airier version\" with vertical and horizontal elements of smaller proportions.<ref name=\"Campus\" /> The title, an invented term, was suggested to him by the final form of the sculpture, which originally sat as one of the many strewn about his [[John Nugent Studio|studio]], the uncoated welded steel gaining a [[patina]] of characteristics of the material itself.<ref name=\"Campus\" />\n\n''Tolsop'' is now located outside the main entrance to the Dr. William Riddell Centre of the University of Regina.<ref name=\"Campus\" />\n\n===Retrospective exhibition and photography===\nIn 1983, his work was the subject of a major retrospective, ''John Nugent: Modernism in Isolation'', organized by the [[MacKenzie Art Gallery]] in Regina.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> In the 1990s, his interests turned to photography.<ref name=\"Long2\" /><ref name=\"Chabun1\">{{cite news |last1=Chabun |first1=Will |title=Sculptor built solid reputation |url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/regina-leader-post/20140319/281608123380631 |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=March 19, 2014}}</ref> Nugent's photography, like his sculpture, was widely collected in Saskatchewan and beyond.<ref name=\"Strombo\" />\n\n===Related pursuits===\nNugent taught at the [[University of Regina]] from 1970 to 1985.<ref name=\"Long2\" />\n\n==Professional affiliations==\nNugent was a member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]].<ref name=RCA1880>{{cite web|title=Members since 1880 |url=http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/ |publisher=Royal Canadian Academy of Arts |url-status=live |accessdate=December 23, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohn Nugent married Florence Keller, and they had five children:<ref name=\"Longman\" /> a son, David, and four daughters, Valerie, Pamela, Patricia and Karen.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news |title=JOHN NUGENT |url=https://www.legacy.com/amp/obituaries/leaderpost/170236972 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=The Regina Leader-Post}}</ref> At the time of his death he had thirteen grandchildren.\n\nNugent died on 12 March 2014, predeceased by his wife, Florence, son, David, grandson, Chad, and great-grandson, Caden.<ref name=\"Obituary\" /> Nugent, his wife, and son are all buried in Lumsden.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lumsden Cemetery |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~cansacem/lumsden.html |website=Saskatchewan Cemeteries Project |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0005847 John Nugent] at ''[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]''\n* [https://esask.uregina.ca/entry/nugent_john_cullen_1921-.jsp John Nugent] at ''The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nugent, John Cullen}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian artist}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n|honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=CAN|size=100%|RCA}}\n|birth_place = [[Montreal]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1921|01|05}}\n|death_place = [[Lumsden, Saskatchewan]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|df=y|2014|03|12|1921|01|05}}\n|known_for   = [[liturgical]] and [[public sculpture]], [[photography]]\n|training    = [[College of Saint Benedict and Saint John's University|Saint John's University]]\n|works = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Louis Riel Memorial (Nugent)|Louis Riel Memorial]]\n*''[[No. 1 Northern]]''\n}}\n|nationality = Canadian\n|spouse      = Florence Keller\n}}\n'''John Cullen Nugent''' was a Canadian artist and educator known primarily for his [[public art]] works, often in the form of [[abstract sculpture]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Montreal]] on 5 January 1921,<ref name=\"Seitz\">{{cite book |last1=Seitz |first1=Elizabeth |title=UNIVERSITY OF REGINA ARCHIVES AND SPECIAL COLLECTIONSTHE DR JOHN ARCHER LIBRARY: 97-43 JOHN NUGENT |date=2009 |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |page=2 |url=https://www.uregina.ca/library/assets/docs/pdf/finding_aids/97_43.pdf |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> the young Nugent attended high school in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] before returning to Canada prior to the [[Second World War]] and joining the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], training at [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] and [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"Longman\">{{cite news |last1=Longman |first1=Harold |title=Ancient art practiced at Lumsden by west's only candlestick maker |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/494968855/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |date=March 9, 1957 |page=2}}</ref> Three years later, Nugent joined the [[Canadian Army]], serving in the [[Provost (military police)|provost corps]] in the 1940s.<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news |title=Influential Sask. artist, John Nugent, dies at 93 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/influential-sask-artist-john-nugent-dies-at-93-1.2578796 |accessdate=22 December 2019 |work=CBC News |agency=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=March 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war, Nugent was discharged and studied art at [[College of Saint Benedict and Saint John's University|St John's University]] ([[Collegeville, Minnesota]]),<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> where he was exposed to liberal ideals and the postwar Catholic renewal in the arts.<ref name=\"Long\">{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Timothy |title=John Cullen Nugent |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/john-cullen-nugent |website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> There, he was apprenticed in sculpture and silversmith work with Donald Humphrey, and later obtained additional training after moving to [[Lumsden, Saskatchewan]] in 1947.<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"SKNAC\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent |url=http://www.sknac.ca/index.php?page=ArtistDetail&id=21 |website=sknac.ca |publisher=Saskatchewan Network for Art Collecting |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nNugent attended the [[Emma Lake, Saskatchewan|Emma Lake]] Artists' Workshops in the 1950s and 1960s, studying with [[Jack Shadbolt]], [[Joseph Plaskett]], [[Will Barnet]], and [[Clement Greenberg]].<ref name=\"SKNAC\" />\n\n==Career in the arts==\n===Religious works and candle making===\nIn Lumsden, Nugent established his first studio (formerly a [[barn]]) and [[bronze casting]] foundry on a 2.7-hectare parcel of land that forms the north slope of the [[Qu\u2019Appelle Valley]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"SKNAC\" /><ref name=\"Studio\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent Studio |url=https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=5859 |website=Canada's Historic Places |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> He received numerous commissions in the decades following,<ref name=\"SKNAC\" /> initially producing religious sculptures in silver and bronze ([[liturgical]] commissions, including chalices and candleholders) while supporting his family as a [[candle|chandler]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /><ref name=\"Long2\">{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Timothy |title=Nugent, John Cullen (1921-) |url=https://esask.uregina.ca/entry/nugent_john_cullen_1921-.jsp |website=The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> According to Timothy Long, these works were \"simplified, yet expressive\": chalices and crucifixes which demonstrated Nugent's interest in modern interpretations of early Christian and [[Romanesque sculpture|Romanesque]] models.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> Candle making was a lucrative sideline, Nugent being the only maker west of [[Windsor, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /> The Shop's wick material was specially woven from [[beeswax]] bought from the beekeepers co-operative processing plant at [[Tisdale, Saskatchewan|Tisdale]] and treated with a solution, the ingredients of which were a [[trade secret]] taught to him by L. H. Shirley, a [[Roman Catholic priest]] in [[Young, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"Longman\" /> \n\n===New studio===\n{{Main|John Nugent Studio}}\nIn 1960, Nugent's candle works in Lumsden burned down. Nugent commissioned [[Clifford Wiens]] to design a new studio with a novel curved, conical design that earned the architect a Massey silver medal.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> The studio was constructed over successive weekends by Nugent and Wiens, with help from fellow artists [[Kenneth Lochhead]] and [[Roy Kiyooka]].<ref name=\"Studio\" /> The studio has been a Provincial Heritage Property since 26 May 2005, the 42nd site so designated, and listed at the online [[Canadian Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"GOS\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent Studio Designated a Provincial Heritage Property |url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2005/november/25/john-nugent-studio-designated-a-provincial-heritage-property |website=Saskatchewan.ca |publisher=[[Government of Saskatchewan]] |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Turn to abstract sculpture===\nResistance from the Church hierarchy and from parishioners led to Nugent abandoning his liturgical work in the 1960s.<ref name=\"Long\" /><ref name=\"Long2\" /> After meeting American sculptor [[David Smith (sculptor)|David Smith]] in New York in 1961, Nugent was in any case gradually shifting to welded steel abstracts, for which he is now best known, and which exhibit what Long calls \"an awkward grace\" in its [[constructivism (art)|constructivist]] [[collage]] of prefabricated steel elements.<ref name=\"Long\"/> He acquired some of the raw materials from the [[SSAB#North American operations|IPSCO Steel]] steel company in Regina, and often gave the pieces names \"to eliminate distraction from the form itself\".<ref name=\"Campus\">{{cite web |title=John Cullen Nugent |url=http://www2.uregina.ca/president/art/outdoor/john-cullen-nugent/ |website=Campus Art Guide |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> Long describes how Nugent's work differentiates itself from that of others:<blockquote>While often incorporating identifiable parts, such as wheels, his sculpture eludes easy metaphorical readings, instead creating meaning through unexpected combinations of forms and materials. Nugent's work represents an independent strain within Canadian abstract steel sculpture without direct ties to the Emma Lake Artists' Workshops or other western Canadian sculptors.<ref name=\"Long2\" /></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Macdonaldstat.jpg|thumb|John A. Macdonald Memorial in [[Victoria Park, Regina]]]]\n\n===Public sculptural works===\nNugent's best known public sculptures are found in the three [[Prairie Provinces]] of Canada, including commissions for places such as the [[Banff Centre]] in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] and the [[Canadian Grain Commission]] building in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"Long\"/> There is a piece in the galleria of the CBC Saskatchewan building in Regina.<ref name=\"Strombo\">{{cite news |title=\u201cHe Taught Us To Consider The Beauty Around Us:\u201d Remembering Saskatchewan Sculptor John Nugent |url=https://www.cbc.ca/strombo/news/john-nugent-1921-2014 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=George Stromboulopoulos Tonight |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Another public commission is at the [[National Capital Commission]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"Long2\" /> More of his work can be found in the collections of the MacKenzie Art Gallery, the [[Robert McLaughlin Gallery]] ([[Oshawa]]), the [[Saskatchewan Arts Board]], the [[University of Regina]], and the [[Winnipeg Art Gallery]].<ref name=\"Long2\" />\n\nOn occasion, controversy was induced by Nugent's work, including commissions by Saskatchewan Premier [[Ross Thatcher]] and the [[Canadian Grain Commission]].<ref name=\"URL\">{{cite web |title=John Nugent |url=https://www.uregina.ca/library/services/archives/collections/art-architecture/nugent.html |website=University of Regina Library |publisher=[[University of Regina]] |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====John A. Macdonald Memorial (1967)====\n{{Main|John A. Macdonald Memorial (Grandmaison)}}\nLocal fundraising for a statue in Regina to comemorate the first [[Prime Minister of Canada]] began in 1891, though the work did not begin until 1966 after Sonia de Grandmaison was commissioned to do the work. Her statue of [[Sir John A. Macdonald]] was cast by Nugent using the \"lost wax technique\" he learned along with candlemaking, in five pieces, which were then [[soldering|soldered]] together.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sonia de Grandmaison: Downtown Regina Public Art Guide |date=2014 |publisher=Regina Downtown Business Improvement District |location=Regina |page=14 |url=https://reginadowntown.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/PublicArtGuide2014-101514web.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020 |chapter=Sir John A. MacDonald (1966-67)}}</ref>\n\n====Louis Riel Memorial (1968)====\n{{Main|Louis Riel Memorial (Nugent)}}\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Riel has significance for people now, and I felt he had to be expressed in contemporary terms.\n| source = John Nugent<ref name=\"MitchellL\">{{cite journal |last1=Mitchell |first1=Linda |title=One sculptor\u2019s racy revenge with an embarrassingly real Riel |journal=Maclean's |date=May 1, 1969 |page=2 |url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1969/5/1/one-sculptors-racy-revenge-with-an-embarrassingly-real-riel |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}} \nIn the lead-up to the [[Canadian Centennial]] in 1967, the Saskatchewan Arts Board recommended that the province should have a new public sculpture.<ref name=\"Chabun0\">{{cite news |last1=Chabun |first1=Will |title=Icons in exile: How Regina's Riel statue and other monuments disappeared from view |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/icons-in-exile-how-reginas-riel-statue-and-other-monuments-disappeared-from-view |accessdate=20 December 2019 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=September 10, 2016}}</ref> To this end, a competition was announced.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent proposed an abstract monument of [[M\u00e9tis]] leader [[Louis Riel]]<ref name=\"URL\" /> in the form of an abstract design in three parts: \"two large plates of steel and a single spike between them\", which Will Chabun suggested could be easily understood as \"two hands reaching out and one other element reaching out to the sky.\"<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> According to Timothy Long, head curator of the [[MacKenzie Art Gallery]], Nugent's idea was to represent an as yet unrealized inspiration.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent's proposal won the competition, but Premier [[Ross Thatcher]] stepped in and made clear his preference for a [[realism (arts)|realistic]] depiction.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> A provincial cabinet meeting followed which included Nugent, representatives from the Board and the [[University of Saskatchewan]], and [[Art McKay]]. All were convinced of the proposal's merit but Premier Thatcher, and he was the only one whose opinion counted.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" />\n\nNugent later said he wanted to refuse but he needed the money. He agreed to design a  sculpture of Riel \"striding forward\", arm raised and pointing upward, maintaining in some way the essence of the original idea.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> Nugent's final submission was of this \"heroic\" figure of Riel, which the artist sculpted as a [[nude]].<ref name=\"URL\" /> Objections were again raised,<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> and Nugent was made to add some form of clothing.<ref name=\"URL\" /> He created a \"cape or vest\" made from wax-coated [[burlap]] and wrapped it around the statue's body, covering the [[genitalia]], though not entirely.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> The statue was unveiled in 1968,<ref name=\"URL\" /> near the legislative building. \n\nAs for those whom Riel originally represented, the M\u00e9tis community, no one was ever consulted by anyone involved in the project at any stage,<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /> and as time passed mounting pressure came from the M\u00e9tis who requested the work be removed from the legislative grounds.<ref name=\"Chabun1\" /> The defunct ArtsSask.ca website noted their criticisms:<blockquote>John Nugent was not of Metis descent and many people in the Metis community were upset because they had no input in the design. Many also found the sculpture of Riel offensive and were glad to see the memorial removed after it had stood in Wascana Park in Regina for 23 years.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /></blockquote>\n\nIn 1991, the sculpture was removed<ref name=\"URL\" /> and relocated to the MacKenzie Art Gallery vault,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mattes |first1=Catherine L. |title=Whose Hero? Images of Louis Riel in Contemporary Art and M\u00e9tis Nationhood |date=1998 |publisher=[[Concordia University]] |location=Montreal, Quebec |page=15 |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk3/ftp04/mq43534.pdf |accessdate=8 January 2020 |format=M.A. thesis}}</ref> along with Nugent's original abstract maquette, where it remains.<ref name=\"Chabun0\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamon |first1=Max |title=[Book review] #226 Rescuing Riel, revising history |website=BC book look |date=December 20, 2017 |url=https://bcbooklook.com/2017/12/20/rescuing-riel-revising-history/ |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''No. 1 Northern'' (1976)====\n{{Main|No. 1 Northern}}\nThis large steel [[abstract sculpture]] is intended as a [[metaphor]] for fields of wheat, represented in multi-layer rectangular shapes and painted the \"brilliant\" yellow of harvest wheat,<ref name=\"White\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Ed |title=Homage to wheat dragged out, dusted off, pieced together |url=https://www.producer.com/1997/05/homage-to-wheat-dragged-out-dusted-off-pieced-together/ |accessdate=18 December 2019 |work=[[The Western Producer]] |date=May 15, 1997}}</ref> designed to represent Canada's hardy top grade, red [[spring wheat]] hybrid of the same name<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\">{{cite book |last1=Anderson-Dolcini |first1=Catherine |title=One-percent for Whom? Canada's Public Works Fine Art Programme, 1964-1978: Its Rise and Demise |date=November 29, 2000 |publisher=[[Carleton University]] |location=Ottawa |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk3/ftp04/MQ57697.pdf |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> that dominate the Prairies in the fall.<ref name=\"White\" /> The work was commissioned following a process begun as a recommendation by the architectural firm [[Smith Carter]] that the recently built [[Canadian Grain Commission]] building should be bestowed with a large scale exterior sculpture.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> Against the objections of Earl Baxter, chairman of the Board of Grain Commissioners, the work was installed in late 1975.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> Baxter canvassed employees, obtaining 300 signatures in protest shortly after the work's 1976 unveiling.<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> The federal government's ''Cultural Property Inventory'' cites complaints from employees and the general public that the work was \"ugly and meaningless\", and \"charges that the piece was dangerous in the winter because someone might walk into it and injure themselves.\"<ref name=\"Alfody\">{{cite book |last1=Alfoldy |first1=Sandra |title=The Allied Arts: Architecture and Craft in Postwar Canada |date=2012 |publisher=[[McGill University|McGill]]-[[Queen's University Press]] |location=[Montreal; Kingston, On.] |isbn=9780773539600 |page=147 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VjYH3-zeFeQC&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=no.+1+northern+nugent&source=bl&ots=hxMuRyCYdY&sig=ACfU3U05oYRTGMF6MKDeN1OD-gbL1C1EeA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoi4KNg8HmAhWVKn0KHbWQDdwQ6AEwBXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=no.%201%20northern%20nugent&f=false |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> The Agriculture Minister [[Eugene Whelan]] called the work \"a waste of taxpayers' moneys.\"<ref name=\"Anderson-Dolcini\" /> \n{{Quote box\n| quote  = Whelan panned me, the press panned me, people in the building panned me... I was lucky to get out of Winnipeg alive.\n| source = John Nugent<ref name=\"Chabun1\"/>\n| width  = 30%\n|align  = right\n}}  \nBy July 1978, Baxter had prevailed. It was reinstalled two years later in front of a [[Revenue Canada]] building, the Winnipeg Taxation Centre on Stapon Road.<ref name=\"WDP\" /><ref name=\"White\" /> At the time, Nugent said he was not interested in the re-installation, upset that his work had not been supported the first time around and since the sculpture was cut into three \"it wasn't his original work anymore.\"<ref name=\"WDP\">{{cite web |title=No. 1 Northern |url=http://winnipegdowntownplaces.blogspot.com/2009/09/no-1-northern.html |website=Winnipeg Downtown Places |accessdate=19 December 2019 |date=September 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the work was quietly moved a second time,<ref name=\"White\" /> this time to a Winnipeg scrapyard in the salvage area, \"in pieces\", unbeknownst to Nugent, who asked for the public's help in finding the piece.<ref name=\"Alfody\" /> A Public Works spokesperson later said it was because new pathways into the building passed too near the sculpture and the department was concerned \"children might climb on it\".<ref name=\"White\" /> In Spring 1997, Nugent discovered what had become of his work had and complained, with many other artists, about the way Public Works stored pieces of art it owned. The department made a commitment to restoring the sculpture and finding a prominent, public setting for it following public reaction to news of its deterioration.<ref name=\"White\" /> Later the same year, almost twenty years after it was removed, ''No. 1 Northern'' was reinstalled in front of the Grain Commission building.<ref name=\"Grain\">{{cite web |title=[303 Main Street] |url=https://www.winnipegarchitecture.ca/303-main-street/ |website=Winnipeg Architecture Foundation |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====''Tolsop'' (1977)====\nInterested in the three-dimensional forms possible by arranging pieces of [[excess supply|surplus]] steel found at the IPSCO site, Nugent welded a piece that has a very different character when viewed from different angles: while a large convex disc dominates all views, its positioning at 45 degrees \"invites the viewer to consider it from other vantage points,\" so that what initially appears to be a large solid, \"flattish\" and angled piece \"morphs into an airier version\" with vertical and horizontal elements of smaller proportions.<ref name=\"Campus\" /> The title, an invented term, was suggested to him by the final form of the sculpture, which originally sat as one of the many strewn about his [[John Nugent Studio|studio]], the uncoated welded steel gaining a [[patina]] of characteristics of the material itself.<ref name=\"Campus\" /> \n\n''Tolsop'' is now located outside the main entrance to the Dr. William Riddell Centre of the University of Regina.<ref name=\"Campus\" />\n\n===Retrospective exhibition and photography===\nIn 1983, his work was the subject of a major retrospective, ''John Nugent: Modernism in Isolation'', organized by the [[MacKenzie Art Gallery]] in Regina.<ref name=\"Long2\" /> In the 1990s, his interests turned to photography.<ref name=\"Long2\" /><ref name=\"Chabun1\">{{cite news |last1=Chabun |first1=Will |title=Sculptor built solid reputation |url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/regina-leader-post/20140319/281608123380631 |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=March 19, 2014}}</ref> Nugent's photography, like his sculpture, was widely collected in Saskatchewan and beyond.<ref name=\"Strombo\" />\n\n===Related pursuits===\nNugent taught at the [[University of Regina]] from 1970 to 1985.<ref name=\"Long2\" />\n\n==Professional affiliations==\nNugent was a member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]].<ref name=RCA1880>{{cite web|title=Members since 1880 |url=http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/ |publisher=Royal Canadian Academy of Arts |url-status=live |accessdate=December 23, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohn Nugent married Florence Keller, and they had five children:<ref name=\"Longman\" /> a son, David, and four daughters, Valerie, Pamela, Patricia and Karen.<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news |title=JOHN NUGENT |url=https://www.legacy.com/amp/obituaries/leaderpost/170236972 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=The Regina Leader-Post}}</ref> At the time of his death he had thirteen grandchildren.\n\nNugent died on 12 March 2014, predeceased by his wife, Florence, son, David, grandson, Chad, and great-grandson, Caden.<ref name=\"Obituary\" /> Nugent, his wife, and son are all buried in Lumsden.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lumsden Cemetery |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~cansacem/lumsden.html |website=Saskatchewan Cemeteries Project |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0005847 John Nugent] at ''[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]''\n* [https://esask.uregina.ca/entry/nugent_john_cullen_1921-.jsp John Nugent] at ''The Encylopedia of Saskatchewan''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nugent, John Cullen}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Montreal]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian photographers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typos for \"Encyclopedia\", replaced: Encylopedia \u2192 Encyclopedia,typo(s) fixed: comemorate \u2192 commemorate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Cullen_Nugent"}
{"title_page": "Planetary science", "text_new": "{{short description|Science of astronomical objects apparently in orbit around one or more stellar objects within a few light years}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2009}}\n[[File:Apollo15DunaTisza.jpg|300px|thumb|upright=1.35|right|Photograph from [[Apollo 15]] orbital unit of the [[rille]]s in the vicinity of the crater [[Aristarchus (crater)|Aristarchus]] on the [[Moon]].]]\n'''Planetary science''' or, more rarely, '''planetology''', is the scientific study of [[planet]]s (including [[Earth]]), [[Natural satellite|moons]], and [[planetary system]]s (in particular those of the [[Solar System]]) and the processes that form them. It studies objects ranging in size from [[micrometeoroid]]s to [[gas giant]]s, aiming to determine their composition, dynamics, formation, interrelations and history. It is a strongly [[interdisciplinary]] field, originally growing from [[astronomy]] and [[earth science]],<ref name=\"Taylor1994\"/> but which now incorporates many disciplines, including [[planetary geology]] (together with [[geochemistry]] and [[geophysics]]), [[cosmochemistry]], [[atmospheric science]], [[oceanography]], [[hydrology]], [[theoretical planetary science]], [[glaciology]], and [[exoplanetology]].<ref name=\"Taylor1994\">{{cite journal\n|last=Taylor\n|first=Stuart Ross\n|date=29 July 2004\n|title=Why can't planets be like stars?\n|journal=Nature\n|pmid=15282586\n|volume=430\n|issue=6999\n|pages=509\n|doi=10.1038/430509a\n|bibcode = 2004Natur.430..509T }}</ref> Allied disciplines include [[space physics]], when concerned with the effects of the [[Sun]] on the bodies of the Solar System, and [[astrobiology]].\n\nThere are interrelated observational and theoretical branches of planetary science. Observational research can involve a combination of [[space exploration]], predominantly with [[robotic spacecraft]] missions using [[remote sensing]], and comparative, experimental work in Earth-based laboratories. The theoretical component involves considerable [[computer simulation]] and mathematical modelling.\n\nPlanetary scientists are generally located in the astronomy and physics or Earth sciences departments of universities or research centres, though there are several purely planetary science institutes worldwide. There are several major conferences each year, and a wide range of [[academic journal|peer-reviewed journals]]. Some planetary scientists work at private research centres and often initiate partnership research tasks.\n\n==History==\nThe history of planetary science may be said to have begun with the Ancient Greek philosopher [[Democritus]], who is reported by [[Hippolytus of Rome|Hippolytus]] as saying <blockquote>The ordered worlds are boundless and differ in size, and that in some there is neither sun nor moon, but that in others, both are greater than with us, and yet with others more in number. And that the intervals between the ordered worlds are unequal, here more and there less, and that some increase, others flourish and others decay, and here they come into being and there they are eclipsed. But that they are destroyed by colliding with one another. And that some ordered worlds are bare of animals and plants and all water.<ref name=\"Philosophumena\">{{cite book|last=Hippolytus (Antipope) |author2=Origen |others=Translation by Francis Legge, F.S.A.|title=Philosophumena|publisher=Society for promoting Christian knowledge|location=Original from Harvard University.|date=1921|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0lrDy9nn1doC&printsec=titlepage|accessdate=22 May 2009|type=Digitized 9 May 2006}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn more modern times, planetary science began in astronomy, from studies of the unresolved planets. In this sense, the original planetary astronomer would be [[Galileo Galilei|Galileo]], who discovered the four largest moons of [[Jupiter]], the mountains on the [[Moon]], and first observed the [[rings of Saturn]], all objects of intense later study. Galileo's study of the lunar mountains in 1609 also began the study of extraterrestrial landscapes: his observation \"that the Moon certainly does not possess a smooth and polished surface\" suggested that it and other worlds might appear \"just like the face of the Earth itself\".<ref name=\"Taylor1994b\">{{cite journal\n|last=Taylor\n|first=Stuart Ross\n|date=1994\n|title=Silent upon a peak in Darien\n|journal=Nature\n|volume=369\n|issue=6477\n|pages=196\u20137\n|bibcode=1994Natur.369..196T\n|doi=10.1038/369196a0\n}}</ref>\n\nAdvances in telescope construction and instrumental resolution gradually allowed increased identification of the atmospheric and surface details of the planets. The Moon was initially the most heavily studied, as it always exhibited details on its surface, due to its proximity to the Earth, and the technological improvements gradually produced more detailed lunar geological knowledge. In this scientific process, the main instruments were astronomical [[optical telescope]]s (and later [[radio telescopes]]) and finally robotic exploratory [[space probe|spacecraft]].\n\nThe Solar System has now been relatively well-studied, and a good overall understanding of the formation and evolution of this planetary system exists. However, there are large numbers of unsolved questions,<ref name=\"SternPlanetarySoc09\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00001956/|title=Ten Things I Wish We Really Knew In Planetary Science|last=Stern|first=Alan|accessdate=2009-05-22}}</ref> and the rate of new discoveries is very high, partly due to the large number of interplanetary spacecraft currently exploring the Solar System.\n\n==Disciplines==\nPlanetary science studies observational and theoretical astronomy, geology (exogeology), atmospheric science, and an emerging subspecialty in [[planetary ocean]]s<!-- this redirect seems to be to just one Solar System liquid body, but the source is a more general discussion of extraterrestrial planetary oceans -->.<ref>[https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/1538-3881/aada02/pdf Is Extraterrestrial Life Suppressed on Subsurface Ocean Worlds due to the Paucity of Bioessential Elements?], The Astronomical Journal, 156:151, October 2018.</ref>\n\n===Planetary astronomy===\nThis is an observational science. Observational researchers are predominantly concerned with the study of the small bodies of the Solar System: those that are observed by telescopes, both optical and radio, so that characteristics of these bodies such as shape, spin, surface materials and weathering are determined, and the history of their formation and evolution can be understood.\n\nTheoretical planetary astronomy is concerned with [[Analytical dynamics|dynamics]]: the application of the principles of [[celestial mechanics]] to the Solar System and [[extrasolar planet]]ary systems. Every planet has its own subject.\n\nPlanet: Subject : Named after (NB: these terms are rarely used)\n\n*[[Mercury (planet)|Mercur]]<nowiki/>y: [[Hermeology|Hermology]] : [[Hermes]]\n*[[Venus]] : [[Geology of Venus|Cytherology]] : [[Kythira|Cythera]]\n*[[Earth]] : [[geology]] : /\n*[[Moon]] : [[Selenology]] : [[Selene]]\n*[[Mars]]: [[Geology of Mars|Areology]] : [[Ares]]\n*[[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] : [[Demeterology]] : [[Demeter]]\n*[[Jupiter]] : [[Zenology]] : [[Zeus]]\n*[[Saturn]] : [[Geology of Saturn|Kronology]] : [[Cronus|Kronos]]\n*[[Uranus]] : [[Uranology|Uranology]] : [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]\n*[[Neptune]] : [[Planetary science of Neptune|Poseidology]] : [[Poseidon]]\n*[[Pluto]] : [[Geology of Pluto|Hadeology]] : [[Hades]]\n*[[Eris (dwarf planet)|Eris]] : [[Eridology]] : [[Eris (mythology)|Eris]]\n\n=== Planetary geology ===\n{{main|Planetary geology}}\n{{see also|Geology of solar terrestrial planets|Icy moon}}\n\nThe best known research topics of planetary geology deal with the planetary bodies in the near vicinity of the Earth: the [[Moon]], and the two neighbouring planets: [[Venus]] and [[Mars]]. Of these, the Moon was studied first, using methods developed earlier on the Earth.\n\n==== Geomorphology ====\n{{main|Geomorphology}}\n\nGeomorphology studies the features on planetary surfaces and reconstructs the history of their formation, inferring the physical processes that acted on the surface. Planetary geomorphology includes the study of several classes of surface features:\n* Impact features ([[multi-ringed basins]], craters)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|date=2015|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|location=New York, NY|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3|editor-last2=Kereszturi|editor-first2=\u00c1kos}}</ref>\n* Volcanic and tectonic features (lava flows, fissures, [[rille]]s)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|date=2015|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|location=New York, NY|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3|editor-last2=Kereszturi|editor-first2=\u00c1kos}}</ref>\n*Glacial features<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|date=2015|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|location=New York, NY|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3|editor-last2=Kereszturi|editor-first2=\u00c1kos}}</ref>\n*Aeolian features<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|date=2015|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|location=New York, NY|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3|editor-last2=Kereszturi|editor-first2=\u00c1kos}}</ref>\n* [[Space weathering]] - erosional effects generated by the harsh environment of space (continuous micro meteorite bombardment, high-energy particle rain, [[impact gardening]]). For example, the thin dust cover on the surface of the [[moon|lunar]] [[regolith]] is a result of micro meteorite bombardment.\n* Hydrological features: the liquid involved can range from water to [[hydrocarbon]] and [[ammonia]], depending on the location within the Solar System. This category includes the study of paleohydrological features (paleochannels, paleolakes).<ref>{{Citation|last=Lefort|first=Alexandra|title=Inverted Channel|date=2015|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|pages=1048\u20131052|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|publisher=Springer New York|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3_202|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|last2=Williams|first2=Rebecca|last3=Korteniemi|first3=Jarmo|editor2-last=Kereszturi|editor2-first=\u00c1kos}}</ref> \n\nThe history of a planetary surface can be deciphered by mapping features from top to bottom according to their [[Law of superposition|deposition sequence]], as first determined on terrestrial [[stratum|strata]] by [[Nicolas Steno]]. For example, [[Stratigraphy|stratigraphic mapping]] prepared the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] astronauts for the field geology they would encounter on their lunar missions. Overlapping sequences were identified on images taken by the [[Lunar Orbiter program]], and these were used to prepare a lunar [[stratigraphic column]] and [[geologic map|geological map]] of the Moon.\n{{further|Geology of the Moon}}\n\n====Cosmochemistry, geochemistry and petrology====\n{{main|Cosmochemistry|Geochemistry|Petrology}}\n\nOne of the main problems when generating hypotheses on the formation and evolution of objects in the Solar System is the lack of samples that can be analysed in the laboratory, where a large suite of tools are available and the full body of knowledge derived from terrestrial geology can be brought to bear. Direct samples from the Moon, [[asteroid]]s and [[Mars]] are present on Earth, removed from their parent bodies and delivered as [[meteorite]]s. Some of these have suffered contamination from the [[oxidise|oxidising]] effect of Earth's atmosphere and the infiltration of the [[biosphere]], but those meteorites collected in the last few decades from [[Antarctica]] are almost entirely pristine.\n\nThe different types of meteorites that originate from the [[asteroid belt]] cover almost all parts of the structure of [[planetary differentiation|differentiated]] bodies: meteorites even exist that come from the core-mantle boundary ([[pallasite]]s). The combination of geochemistry and observational astronomy has also made it possible to trace the [[HED meteorite]]s back to a specific asteroid in the main belt, [[4 Vesta]].\n\nThe comparatively few known [[Martian meteorites]] have provided insight into the geochemical composition of the Martian crust, although the unavoidable lack of information about their points of origin on the diverse Martian surface has meant that they do not provide more detailed constraints on theories of the evolution of the Martian [[lithosphere]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.uwyo.edu |title = UW - Laramie, Wyoming &#124; University of Wyoming}}</ref> As of July 24, 2013 65 samples of Martian meteorites have been discovered on Earth. Many were found in either Antarctica or the Sahara Desert.\n\nDuring the Apollo era, in the [[Apollo program]], 384 kilograms of [[lunar sample]]s were collected and transported to the Earth, and 3 [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Luna programme|Luna]] robots also delivered [[regolith]] samples from the Moon. These samples provide the most comprehensive record of the composition of any Solar System body beside the Earth. The numbers of lunar meteorites are growing quickly in the last few years \u2013<ref>{curator.jsc.nasa.gov/antmet/lmc/lmcintro.pdf}</ref> as of\nApril 2008 there are 54 meteorites that have been officially classified as lunar.\nEleven of these are from the US Antarctic meteorite collection, 6 are from the Japanese\nAntarctic meteorite collection, and the other 37 are from hot desert localities in Africa,\nAustralia, and the Middle East. The total mass of recognized lunar meteorites is close to\n50&nbsp;kg.\n\n====Geophysics====\n{{main|Geophysics|Space physics}}\nSpace probes made it possible to collect data in not only the visible light region, but in other areas of the electromagnetic spectrum. The planets can be characterized by their force fields: gravity and their magnetic fields, which are studied through geophysics and space physics.\n\nMeasuring the changes in acceleration experienced by spacecraft as they orbit has allowed fine details of the [[gravity field]]s of the planets to be mapped. For example, in the 1970s, the gravity field disturbances above [[lunar maria]] were measured through lunar orbiters, which led to the discovery of concentrations of mass, [[Mass concentration (astronomy)|mascons]], beneath the Imbrium, Serenitatis, Crisium, Nectaris and Humorum basins.\n[[File:Magnetosphere rendition.jpg|right|thumb|The [[solar wind]] is deflected by the magnetosphere (not to scale)]]\nIf a planet's [[magnetic field]] is sufficiently strong, its interaction with the solar wind forms a [[magnetosphere]] around a planet. Early space probes discovered the gross dimensions of the terrestrial magnetic field, which extends about 10 Earth radii towards the Sun. The [[solar wind]], a stream of charged particles, streams out and around the terrestrial magnetic field, and continues behind the magnetic tail, hundreds of Earth radii downstream. Inside the magnetosphere, there are relatively dense regions of solar wind particles, the [[Van Allen radiation belt]]s.\n\nGeophysics includes [[seismology]] and [[tectonophysics]], [[geophysical fluid dynamics]], [[mineral physics]], [[geodynamics]], [[mathematical geophysics]], and [[geophysical surveying]].\n\n{{anchor|planetary geodesy}}<!-- used by incoming redirect -->\nPlanetary [[geodesy]], (also known as planetary geodetics) deals with the measurement and representation of the planets of the Solar System, their [[gravitation]]al fields and geodynamic phenomena ([[polar motion]] in three-dimensional, time-varying space. The science of geodesy has elements of both astrophysics and planetary sciences. The shape of the Earth is to a large extent the result of its rotation, which causes its equatorial bulge, and the competition of geologic processes such as the collision of plates and of [[Volcano|vulcanism]], resisted by the Earth's [[gravity]] field. These principles can be applied to the solid surface of Earth ([[orogeny]]; Few mountains are higher than {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}}, few deep sea trenches deeper than that because quite simply, a mountain as tall as, for example, {{convert|15|km|0|abbr=on}}, would develop so much [[pressure]] at its base, due to gravity, that the rock there would become [[plastic]], and the mountain would slump back to a height of roughly {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}} in a geologically insignificant time. Some or all of these geologic principles can be applied to other planets besides Earth. For instance on Mars, whose surface gravity is much less, the largest volcano, [[Olympus Mons]], is {{convert|27|km|0|abbr=on}} high at its peak, a height that could not be maintained on Earth. The Earth [[geoid]] is essentially the figure of the Earth abstracted from its topographic features. Therefore, the Mars geoid is essentially the figure of Mars abstracted from its topographic features. [[Surveying]] and [[map]]ping are two important fields of application of geodesy.\n\n===Atmospheric science===\n{{main|Atmospheric science|Global climate model}}\n[[File:Jupiter.jpg|right|thumb|Cloud bands clearly visible on [[Jupiter]]. ]]\nThe [[atmosphere]] is an important transitional zone between the solid planetary surface and the higher rarefied [[Ionisation|ionizing]] and radiation belts. Not all planets have atmospheres: their existence depends on the mass of the planet, and the planet's distance from the Sun&nbsp;\u2014 too distant and frozen atmospheres occur. Besides the four [[gas giant]] planets, almost all of the [[terrestrial planets]] ([[Earth's atmosphere|Earth]], [[Atmosphere of Venus|Venus]], and [[Atmosphere of Mars|Mars]]) have significant atmospheres. Two moons have significant atmospheres: [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] and [[Neptune]]'s moon [[Atmosphere of Triton|Triton]]. A tenuous atmosphere exists around [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]].\n\nThe effects of the [[Planet#Rotation|rotation rate]] of a planet about its axis can be seen in atmospheric streams and currents. Seen from space, these features show as bands and eddies in the cloud system, and are particularly visible on Jupiter and Saturn.\n\n==Comparative planetary science==\n\n{{main|Comparative planetary science}}\n\nPlanetary science frequently makes use of the method of comparison to give a greater understanding of the object of study. This can involve comparing the dense atmospheres of Earth and Saturn's moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], the evolution of outer Solar System objects at different distances from the Sun, or the geomorphology of the surfaces of the terrestrial planets, to give only a few examples.\n\nThe main comparison that can be made is to features on the Earth, as it is much more accessible and allows a much greater range of measurements to be made. Earth analogue studies are particularly common in planetary geology, geomorphology, and also in atmospheric science.\n\nThe use of terrestrial analogues was first described by Gilbert (1886).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Planetary Landforms|date=2015|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-3133-6|editor-last=Hargitai|editor-first=Henrik|location=New York, NY|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-4614-3134-3|editor-last2=Kereszturi|editor-first2=\u00c1kos}}</ref>\n\n==Professional activity==\n\n===Journals===\n*''[[Earth and Planetary Science Letters]]''\n*''[[Earth, Moon, and Planets]]''\n*''[[Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta]]''\n*''[[Icarus (journal)|Icarus]]''\n*''[[Journal of Geophysical Research|Journal of Geophysical Research\u2014Planets]]''\n*''[[Meteoritics and Planetary Science]]''\n*''[[Planetary and Space Science]]''\n\n===Professional bodies===\n* [[Division for Planetary Sciences]] (DPS) of the [[American Astronomical Society]]\n* [[American Geophysical Union]]\n* [[Meteoritical Society]]\n* [[Europlanet]]\n\n===Major conferences===\n* [[Lunar and Planetary Science Conference]] (LPSC), organized by the [[Lunar and Planetary Institute]] in Houston. Held annually since 1970, occurs in March.\n* [[Division for Planetary Sciences]] (DPS) meeting held annually since 1970 at a different location each year, predominantly within the mainland US.  Occurs around October.\n* [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU) annual Fall meeting in December in San Francisco.\n* [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU) Joint Assembly (co-sponsored with other societies) in April\u2013May, in various locations around the world.\n* [[Meteoritical Society]] annual meeting, held during the Northern Hemisphere summer, generally alternating between North America and Europe.\n* [[European Planetary Science Congress]] (EPSC), held annually around September at a location within Europe.\n\nSmaller workshops and conferences on particular fields occur worldwide throughout the year.\n\n===Major institutions===\nThis non-exhaustive list includes those institutions and universities with major groups of people working in planetary science. Alphabetical order is used.\n\n====National space agencies====\n* [[Canadian Space Agency]] (CSA). Annual budget CAD $488.7 million (2013\u20132014). \n* [[China National Space Administration]] (CNSA) (People's Republic of China). Budget $0.5-1.3 Billion (est.).\n* [[CNES|Centre national d'\u00e9tudes spatiales]] French National Centre of Space Research,Budget \u20ac1.920 Billion (2012). \n* [[German Aerospace Center|Deutsches Zentrum f\u00fcr Luft- und Raumfahrt e.V.]], (German: abbreviated DLR), the German Aerospace Center. Budget $2 Billion (2010).\n* [[European Space Agency]] (ESA). Budget $5.51 Billion (2013).\n* [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] (ISRO),\n* [[Israel Space Agency]] (ISA),\n* [[Italian Space Agency]] Budget ~$1 Billion (2010).\n* [[Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency]] (JAXA). Budget $2.15 Billion (2012).\n* [[NASA]]: Considerable number of research groups, including the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory|JPL]], [[Goddard Space Flight Center|GSFC]], [[NASA Ames Research Center|Ames]]. Budget $18.724 Billion (2011).\n* [[National Space Organization]] (Taiwan).\n* [[Russian Federal Space Agency]] Budget $5.61 Billion (2013).\n* [[UK Space Agency]] (UKSA).\n\n====Other institutions====\n{{external links|section=y|date=January 2020}}\n*[[Arctic Planetary Science Institute]]\n*[https://asu.edu Arizona State University]'s [https://sese.asu.edu School of Earth and Space Exploration]\n*The [[Australian National University]]'s [https://web.archive.org/web/20090928025201/http://rsaa.anu.edu.au/PSI/Welcome.html Planetary Science Institute]\n* [[Brown University]] [http://www.planetary.brown.edu/ Planetary Geosciences Group]\n* [[Caltech]]'s [http://www.gps.caltech.edu/ Division of Geological and Planetary Sciences] and [http://web.gps.caltech.edu/options/planetary/ Planetary Sciences subdivision]\n* [[Cornell University]]'s  [http://www.geo.cornell.edu/eas/PeoplePlaces/Faculty/matt/planetary/ Space and Planetary Science]\n*[[Curtin University]]'s [https://scieng.curtin.edu.au/schools/school-of-earth-and-planetary-sciences/ School of Earth and Planetary Sciences]\n* [[Florida Institute of Technology]]'s [http://cos.fit.edu/pss/ Department of Physics and Space Sciences]\n* [[Johns Hopkins University|Johns Hopkins University's]] [http://www.jhuapl.edu/ Applied Physics Laboratory] \n* [[Lunar and Planetary Institute]]\n* [[Max Planck Institute for Solar System Research]]'s [http://www.mps.mpg.de/planetary-science Department Planets and Comets]\n* [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] [http://eapsweb.mit.edu/ Dept. of Earth, Atmospheric and Planetary Sciences]\n* [[Open University]] [http://pssri.open.ac.uk/