, near the village of [[S\u00fcrmeli]], stands the ruins of the medieval city of Surmari, with a citadel whose surviving walls date from 1224.  A ruinous 13th century Armenian [[caravanserai]] known as the \"Caravanserai of Zor\" is another historical structure near I\u011fd\u0131r.<ref>[http://www.virtualani.org/zor/ Caravansarai of Zor]. VirtualAni.org.</ref>\n\n===The Genocide Memorial===\n[[File:IgdirGenocideMuseum.jpg|thumb|right|Turkish Martyrs' Memorial and Museum]]\n{{main|I\u011fd\u0131r Genocide Memorial and Museum}}\nIn August 1997, construction started on the \"I\u011fd\u0131r Soyk\u0131r\u0131m An\u0131t-M\u00fczesi\" (I\u011fd\u0131r Genocide Memorial and Museum). Turkish authorities erected the monument to commemorate massacres of [[Turkish people|Turks]] by [[Armenians]] during World War I and the [[Turkish\u2013Armenian War]] during the [[Turkish War of Independence]]. The Turkish argument states that \"A need was expressed for the erection of this monument and this opinion was stated as follows in the final declaration of the International Symposium on Historical Realities and Armenians, held in I\u011fd\u0131r from 24 to 26 April 1965. The Symposium resolved that a monument of martyrs should be erected in I\u011fd\u0131r and a cemetery for martyrs should be established in Oba Village in order to eternalise the memories of more than one million Turks that fell in Eastern Anatolia and to give a similar answer to those declaring 24 April as a genocide day and to the monuments erected in many places of the world for the alleged genocide perpetrated against the Armenians.\"<ref name=\"ErmeniSorunu\">\"[http://www.ermenisorunu.gen.tr/english/massacres/igdir.html Igdir Genocide Monument and Museum].\"</ref>\n\nIt was opened on October 5, 1999 by Turkish Minister of State [[Ramazan Mirzao\u011flu]]. Its height from ground level is 43.5 metres. The monument's design contains symbols related to Turkish self-identity, history, and legends. The upper structure consists of five upright swords, their points touching to resemble Mount Ararat. On the hilt of the swords are a series of reliefs. Beneath the monument are a series of rooms intended to house a museum. The granite for the monument's swords was brought from China and other materials, such as marble, granite, and ceramics, were brought from other regions of Turkey.<ref name=\"ErmeniSorunu\"/>\n\nIts construction is explained as a counter-argument by the Turks that Armenians also perpetrated massacres against Turks.<ref>[[Tessa Hofmann|Hofmann, Tessa]]. \"[http://www.armenian.ch/asa/Docs/faae02.pdf Armenians in Turkey: A Critical Assessment of the situation of the Armenian Minority in the Turkish Republic].\" Forum of Armenian Associations in Europe. October 2002, p. 32.</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nI\u011fd\u0131r's culture is part of the larger [[culture of Turkey]]. The rising agricultural production and the opening of a border gate with [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhchivan]] in 1992 have enabled the town to be livelier and wealthier than its neighbours in the generally impoverished eastern Turkey. There are many cafes and restaurants. The best-known dish is a meat stew called ''bozba\u015f''.<ref>\"S\u00fcrmeli \u00c7ukurda I\u011fd\u0131r\", Ziya Zakir Acar, 2002</ref>\n[[File:I\u011fd\u0131rdan A\u011fr\u0131 Da\u011f\u0131.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Mount Ararat]] as seen from I\u011fd\u0131r]]\n\n==Media==\nI\u011fd\u0131r has 12 local daily and weekly newspapers.<ref>Her Y\u00f6n\u00fcyle I\u011fd\u0131r\", Ziya Zakir Acar, 2004</ref>{{Page needed|date=August 2011}} The most prominent of these is ''Ye\u015fil I\u011fd\u0131r'' which has been published since 1 September 1955.\n\n==Economy==\nThe main economic activities in I\u011fd\u0131r are the commerce of agricultural and animal products.<ref name=islamans/>\n\nThe city of I\u011fd\u0131r is located between [[Kars Province|Kars]] and [[A\u011fr\u0131 province|A\u011fr\u0131]]. Despite the fact that it has three strategically important neighbours, the border gate to Armenia is closed and there is no direct access to Iran, therefore this situation diminishes economic possibilities.\n\nAbout 70% percent of [[Mount Ararat]]'s area lies within I\u011fd\u0131r's borders, however the investments for developing tourism in Mt. Ararat is paid to A\u011fr\u0131 Municipality.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{further|Demographics of Turkey}}\n\nAccording to the Russian family lists accounts from 1886, of the total 71,066 inhabitants of the districts 34,351 were Azerbaijanis (48.3%, mentioned as 'Tatars' in the source), 22,096 Armenians (31.1%) and 14,619 Kurds (20.6%).<ref name=\"Ethnokavkaz\"/> According to the [[Russian Empire Census]] in 1897 I\u011fd\u0131r had a population of 4,680, of which 3,934 (84%) were [[Armenians]], and 559 (12%) were [[Russians]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}} ''\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0418\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0438, 1897 \u0433.'' (Erivanskaya Guberniya), N. A. Troynitskii, Saint Petersburg, 1904, p. 144.</ref>\n\nToday, I\u011fd\u0131r has a mixed population of [[Azerbaijanis]] (who form the majority)<ref>{{cite news|title=Azerbaijanis Flock to Turkish Town|url=https://iwpr.net/global-voices/azerbaijanis-flock-turkish-town|agency=[[Institute for War and Peace Reporting]]|publisher=[[Institute for War and Peace Reporting]]|date=9 November 2007|quote=A majority of Igdir\u2019s 60,000 inhabitants are now Azerbaijani.}}</ref><ref>Population policy in Turkey, Erhard Franz, page 293</ref>\u2014[[Kurds]] and [[Turkish people|Turks]].<ref>{{in lang|tr}} Yilmaer, Esat. [http://webarsiv.hurriyet.com.tr/2002/08/05/162199.asp Sevilen valiyle \u2018sava\u015f\u2019 MHP'ye kaybettirmi\u015f].\" ''[[H\u00fcrriyet]]''. August 5, 2002.</ref> The spring festival [[Nowruz]] is widely celebrated in I\u011fd\u0131r.\n\n[[File:A\u011fr\u0131 Da\u011f\u0131'ndan I\u011fd\u0131r \u015eehri.jpg|thumb|right|250px|I\u011fd\u0131r as seen from [[Mount Ararat]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=200\n! colspan=4 |I\u011fd\u0131r centrum population\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 2007\n| align=\"right\" | 75,927\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 2000\n| align=\"right\" | 59,880\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 1997\n| align=\"right\" | 44,334\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 1990\n| align=\"right\" | 35,858\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |  1985\n| align=\"right\" | 29,460\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |  1980\n| align=\"right\" | 24,352\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |  1975\n| align=\"right\" | 29,542\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |  1970\n| align=\"right\" | 21,420\n|}\n\n== Transport ==\nTransport to I\u011fd\u0131r is via roads or air. [[I\u011fd\u0131r Airport]], opened in 2012, serves the city with internal flights to [[Istanbul]] and [[Ankara]]. Regular bus services connect the city to major national and regional centres. There is, as of 2016, no rail transport to I\u011fd\u0131r, but it will be a stop on the Nakhchivan-Kars railway when it is completed.<ref name=\"serka\">{{cite web|title=I\u011fd\u0131r'\u0131n Sosyoekonomik Durumu|url=http://www.serka.gov.tr/store/file/common/9fec328c4f394bb5e9987f31ff05853a.pdf|publisher=Turkish Agency on the Development of Border Areas|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Volkan Atlas]], Turkish investor in Azerbaijan who has expanded monopoly of various shops in the city of Baku.\n* [[Avetis Aharonian]], Armenian politician \n* [[Servet \u00c7etin]], Turkish national football team player of [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijani]] descent\n* [[Eduard Isabekyan]], Armenian painter\n* [[Drastamat Kanayan]], Armenian military commander\n* [[Sinan O\u011fan]], Turkish [[politician]];<ref>[http://www.news.az/articles/38287 Head of Turkey-Azerbaijan association becomes deputy of Turkish parliament] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027073414/http://www.news.az/articles/38287 |date=2014-10-27 }}</ref> [[2011 Turkish general election|won a seat]] in the Turkish parliament in 2011 with the [[right-wing]] [[Nationalist Movement Party]]<ref>[http://news.day.az/politics/272936.html Azeri Elected to Turkish Parliament]. ''Day.az''. 13 June 2011.</ref>\n* [[\u015eahin Yakut]], Turkish kickboxer and MMA fighter\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Turkey}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 sister cities===\nI\u011fd\u0131r is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* [[File:Flag of Azerbaijan.svg|20px]] [[Sharur]], [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic]] [[Azerbaijan]]\n* [[File:Flag of Azerbaijan.svg|20px]] [[Shamakhi]], [[Azerbaijan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|I\u011fd\u0131r}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070505063154/http://www.igdir.bel.tr/eng_index.asp Official website of the I\u011fd\u0131r Municipality]\n* {{in lang|tr}} [http://www.igdir.gov.tr Official website of the I\u011fd\u0131r Province]\n* {{in lang|tr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20080511132220/http://www.igdirhaber.net/ I\u011fd\u0131r's news website]\n\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=I\u011fd\u0131r}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Igdir}}\n[[Category:I\u011fd\u0131r| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Districts of I\u011fd\u0131r Province]]\n[[Category:Erivan Governorate]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typos for \"Encyclopedia\", replaced: Enyclopaedia \u2192 Encyclopaedia, Encyclopaedia Iranica \u2192 Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I%C4%9Fd%C4%B1r"}
